english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Writings of Master Han Mungyeong of Yuhangol
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Among the illustrious statesmen of recent times stands Master Han Mungyeong of Yuhangol—a man whose conduct towered high and whose insight shone clear, becoming a model for scholars of his age. His calligraphy was unrivaled, commanding the reverence of all. Honored by the royal court, he served long in positions of influence, offering wise counsel that brought manifold benefit to the realm. In his dealings with others, he ever practiced sincerity, never given to idle praise or blame. Those who walked beside him—such luminaries as Master Mugan and Master Pyeongje—were themselves exemplars of refinement, and together they cultivated one another in mutual admiration, reaching the very pinnacle of virtue.

    When the Master oversaw the selection of officials, I, though but a junior scholar, had the fortune to serve as his assistant. One day, while we kept watch together at the palace, I sat eating while reading a book. The Master smiled and said, "I see your cultivation of reverence remains incomplete. With food in your mouth and eyes upon a page, how can your heart be undivided?" His words struck me with sudden shame. From that moment forward, though I could not always practice what he taught, I never dared forget those words—they became my lifelong treasure. All his guidance was of this character.

    The Master was renowned early for his poetry, praised by the great scholars Iksae and Gajeong. In his later years, his art only deepened. He held firmly to principle, and when others sought his counsel, he gave generously of his insight. Even celebrated poets like Doeun made pilgrimage to him for correction, accepting his judgments with gratitude and departing enriched. Through his kindness, even one so unworthy as myself received his nod of approval.

    The Master had four sons, all of whom proved worthy. Three rose to highest honors in the examinations, inheriting his legacy and blessed with fortune—all fruits of his teachings. When he presided over the examination system, those selected were renowned officials and accomplished men. The world marveled at the fineness of his discernment.

    Alas! His words, his conduct, his talents and wisdom—all were worthy of becoming a model for gentlemen and scholars. Yet poetry was merely the overflow of his excellence. In his later years, living in leisure and dwelling in the same village as Master Mugan, the two elders would stroll together, composing verses in turn. Their poetic grace and lofty spirit can be glimpsed in reading their works. Yuhangol was the name of his village, which he adopted as his pen name. During his lifetime, unsatisfied with his writings, he did not preserve them. After his passing, his sons gathered scattered manuscripts, recovering but a handful of poems—truly like a single hair upon the great mountain. Yet viewing what remains, one finds such simplicity and tranquility, such purity soaring beyond expectation—like hearing jade-stone ring with clarity and lingering resonance. Was there much to lose? No—there was little lost at all. His second son, Sangjil, consulted with his brothers on publishing these works in print. Because I served the Master long, they asked me to write this preface. I could not refuse. Thus I have briefly set forth the Master's words and deeds to stand at the head of this collection, so that those who read his poetry in ages to come may know that his worth lies not in verse alone, but in all that he exemplified.
  footnotes:
    - 'Yuhangol (柳巷): Both a place name and the Master''s chosen pen name, meaning ''Willow Alley'''
    - The royal figure 'Gongminwang' refers to King Gongmin, who ruled in the Goryeo period
    - The phrase 'jade-stone ring with clarity' alludes to the pure, crystalline quality of his verse, suggesting both technical perfection and spiritual refinement
